    "type" :
    
    
    "static"
    ,
    
    "inputs" : {
    
    
    "para" :
    true,
    
    "html" :
    
    
    "Due to the composition of different materials in the friction layer and support body, the friction surfaces have an non-critical crack pattern (stress-relief microstructure). Individual relaxation cracks sometimes run along the perforated bores."
    
    }
    
    }
    ,
    
    {
    
    
    "type" :
    
    
    "static"
    ,
    
    "inputs" : {
    
    
    "para" :
    true,
    
    "html" :
    
    
    "The stress-relief microstructure results from the way in which the brake disc surface is manufactured and does not pose a risk to safety. There is also no danger of the friction layers flaking off from the support body because the friction layers are virtually free of internal stresses as a result of the stress-relief microstructure."
    
    }
    
    }
    ,
    
    {
    
    
    "type" :
    
    
    "static"
    ,
    
    "inputs" : {
    
    
    "para" :
    true,
    
    "html" :
    
    
    "The stress-relief microstructure in PCCB brake disc friction surfaces does not constitute a wear criterion, is sometimes clearly visible in new brake discs and can be significantly different on the brake disc hub side and the side opposite the hub."
    
    }
    
    }
